 incredibly productive waters of the Gulf of California and beyond, to oceans around the world. Kelsey brings us along as she talks to leading cetacean researchers and marine ecologists about their intriguing discoveries. We encounter humpback whales that build nets from bubbles, gain a disturbing maternal perspective on the dolphin-tuna issue, uncover intimate details about whale sex, and contemplate the meaning of the complex social networks that exist in the seas. What emerges alongside these fascinating snapshots of whale culture is a dizzying sense of the tremendous speed with which we are changing the oceans' ecosystems—through overfishing, noise pollution, even real estate development. Watching Giants introduces a world of immense interconnectivity and beauty—one that is now facing imminent peril.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 29. Mai 2023) 0aWhaleszMexicozCalifornia, Gulf of. 0aWhales. 7aNATURE / Animals.2bisacsh  aaquatic mammals.  ablue whales.  acetacean researchers.  aconservationist.  acreatures.  adolphin tuna issue.  adolphins.  aecosystem.  aenvironmentalism.  agulf of california.  ahumpback whales.  amarine ecology.  amarine mammals.  amarine pollution.  amotherhood.  anets from bubbles.  anoise pollution.  aocean.  aoceanic creatures.  aopen ocean.  aoverfishing.  apersonal experiences.  aphenomenon.  asave the whales.  asocial networks.  asperm whales.  aswimming.  awhale sex.  awhales.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUniversity of California Press Backlist Package 2000-2013z97831106904220 cprintz978052024976940uhttps://doi.org/10.1525/978052094221940uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780520942219423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780520942219/original  a978-3-11-069042-2  University of California Press